\section{Initial-state mapping}{


MOON's engine internally distinguishes two normal-weight states:
\code{N_always} (currently NW, never previously OW or OB) and \code{N_prev}
(currently NW but previously overweight or obese at some earlier age).
These are conflated in the user-facing \code{init_prev} parameter, which is
a 4-vector \code{c(NW, OW, OB1, OB2)}.

\strong{Default mapping}: all NW initial mass is placed in \code{N_always} and
\code{N_prev} starts at 0. Both states then evolve independently per the
engine's six-state transition matrix; mass flows into \code{N_prev} only as
OW / OB1 / OB2 individuals regress to NW during the simulation.

This reflects the published MOON model (Bjørnelv et al. 2021), where
the Norwegian birth cohort enters at age 2 with no obesity history.

\strong{Overriding the default}: there is no separate
\code{init_n_always_share} argument. Instead, supply a full six-element
initial-state vector via \code{tp_overrides$init_prev}; the engine uses it
verbatim and skips the 4-to-6 mapping. Example, for a hypothetical
cohort whose NW members had previously been overweight:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode">}}\preformatted{tp_overrides = list(
  init_prev = c(N_always = 0.5, N_prev = 0.4,
                OW = 0.07, OB1 = 0.02, OB2 = 0.01, D = 0)
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

\strong{Pairing with \code{start_age}}: \code{init_prev} is the BMI distribution at
the cohort entry age. If you shift the entry age — by mutating
\code{params$start_age} or by passing \code{tp_overrides$start_age} — also
supply a matching \code{init_prev} (mutate \code{params$init_prev} for the
former, pass \code{tp_overrides$init_prev} for the latter), or the cohort
will enter at the new age with the wrong BMI distribution. The
validator cannot catch this. See
\code{vignette("moon-customizing", package = "moon")} §6 for the
bootstrap recipe.
}

